            <section class="prose">
              <h2>Understanding Plate Tectonics and Plate Velocity</h2>
              <p>
                Plate tectonics describes how Earth’s rigid outer shell (the
                lithosphere) is broken into large plates that move slowly over
                the underlying, softer asthenosphere. These plates interact at
                their boundaries, creating earthquakes, volcanoes, mountain
                ranges, and ocean basins.
              </p>
              <p>
                Modern geodesy (especially GPS measurements) shows that tectonic
                plates move at speeds of a few to more than 100 millimeters per
                year. Over millions of years, even these slow motions add up to
                thousands of kilometers of displacement.
              </p>

              <h3>Key types of plate boundaries</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Divergent boundaries</strong> – plates move apart,
                  creating new crust at mid-ocean ridges.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Convergent boundaries</strong> – plates move toward
                  each other; one may subduct beneath the other or they may
                  collide to form mountains.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Transform boundaries</strong> – plates slide
                  horizontally past each other, such as along the San Andreas
                  Fault.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Formulas used in the Plate Tectonics Calculator</h2>

              <h3>1. Distance traveled by a single plate</h3>
              <p>
                The basic relationship between velocity, time, and distance is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Distance</strong> = Velocity × Time</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Velocity is typically in mm/yr, cm/yr, or km/Myr.</li>
                  <li>
                    Time is in years, thousands of years (kyr), or millions of
                    years (Myr).
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                To keep units consistent, the calculator converts everything
                internally to kilometers:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>1 mm = 10<sup>−6</sup> km</p>
                <p>1 cm = 10<sup>−5</sup> km</p>
                <p>1 Myr = 10<sup>6</sup> years</p>
              </div>
              <p>For example, a plate moving at 50 mm/yr for 10 Myr:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Velocity = 50 mm/yr = 50 × 10<sup>−6</sup> km/yr = 5 × 10<sup
                    >−5</sup
                  >
                  km/yr
                </p>
                <p>
                  Time = 10 Myr = 10 × 10<sup>6</sup> yr = 10<sup>7</sup> yr
                </p>
                <p>Distance = 5 × 10<sup>−5</sup> × 10<sup>7</sup> = 500 km</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Relative motion between two plates</h3>
              <p>
                Along a line connecting two plates, the
                <strong>relative velocity</strong> is the difference between
                their velocities:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>v<sub>rel</sub> = v<sub>A</sub> − v<sub>B</sub></p>
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If <strong>v<sub>rel</sub> &gt; 0</strong> (in the chosen
                  direction), the plates are moving apart (divergence).
                </li>
                <li>
                  If <strong>v<sub>rel</sub> &lt; 0</strong>, they are moving
                  toward each other (convergence).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>The change in separation over time is then:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Δd = v<sub>rel</sub> × t</p>
              </div>

              <h2>Worked examples</h2>

              <h3>
                Example 1 – How far has a plate moved since the dinosaurs?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Suppose a plate has an average velocity of 30 mm/yr over the
                last 100 million years.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Velocity = 30 mm/yr = 30 × 10<sup>−6</sup> km/yr</p>
                <p>Time = 100 Myr = 100 × 10<sup>6</sup> yr</p>
                <p>
                  Distance = 30 × 10<sup>−6</sup> × 100 × 10<sup>6</sup> = 3,000
                  km
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                That’s roughly the width of the Atlantic Ocean at mid-latitudes,
                illustrating how plate motion shapes continents and oceans over
                geologic time.
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Convergence rate at a subduction zone</h3>
              <p>
                Plate A moves toward the trench at 60 mm/yr, while Plate B on
                the other side moves toward the trench at 20 mm/yr. Taking
                motion toward the trench as positive:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>v<sub>A</sub> = +60 mm/yr</p>
                <p>
                  v<sub>B</sub> = −20 mm/yr (moving away from the trench in our
                  sign convention)
                </p>
                <p>
                  v<sub>rel</sub> = v<sub>A</sub> − v<sub>B</sub> = 60 − (−20) =
                  80 mm/yr
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The plates converge at 80 mm/yr. Over 5 Myr, the total
                convergence would be:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Distance = 80 mm/yr × 5 Myr = 80 × 10<sup>−6</sup> km/yr × 5 ×
                  10<sup>6</sup> yr = 400 km
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Limitations and good practice</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Average velocities only:</strong> Real plate speeds
                  vary over time; this tool assumes a constant average velocity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>1D motion along a line:</strong> The relative motion
                  calculator treats motion along a single line, not full 3D
                  vectors on a sphere.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Educational use:</strong> For research-grade work,
                  consult published plate motion models (e.g., NUVEL-1A, MORVEL)
                  and geophysical datasets.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ accordion -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Plate Tectonics FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full flex justify-between items-center px-4 py-3 text-left faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >How fast do tectonic plates move?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Most tectonic plates move between about 5 and 100
                    millimeters per year (mm/yr). Slow plates may move only a
                    few mm/yr, while fast plates like the Pacific Plate can
                    exceed 100 mm/yr in some regions. Although this is very slow
                    on human timescales, over millions of years it produces
                    thousands of kilometers of motion.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full flex justify-between items-center px-4 py-3 text-left faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >How do scientists measure plate velocities?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Plate velocities are measured using a combination of GPS
                    networks, seafloor magnetic anomalies, hotspot tracks, and
                    geological reconstructions of past plate positions.
                    Continuous GPS stations can detect motions of a few
                    millimeters per year, allowing precise estimates of
                    present-day plate motion.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full flex justify-between items-center px-4 py-3 text-left faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >What is the difference between absolute and relative
                      plate motion?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Absolute plate motion describes how a plate moves relative
                    to a fixed reference frame, such as hotspots or Earth’s deep
                    mantle. Relative plate motion describes how one plate moves
                    with respect to another plate. Earthquakes, volcanoes, and
                    mountain building are controlled mainly by relative motions
                    at plate boundaries.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full flex justify-between items-center px-4 py-3 text-left faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >Can this calculator tell me earthquake risk?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    No. The calculator only estimates average plate motion and
                    relative convergence or divergence. Earthquake hazard
